column104: The publication year of the paper with the title 'Continuous Architecture: Towards the Goldilocks Zone and Away from Vicious Circles' is 2019, which is later than the publication year of the paper with the title 'Designing Robust Software Systems through Parametric Markov Chain Synthesis', which is 2017.

column4: The “Model‐Based Analysis of Microservice Resiliency Patterns” paper is evaluated by means of model‐based experiments and quantitative simulation of resiliency patterns – an approach aligned with evaluation research (as it is classified under “Research Level 1”). In contrast, “Supporting Architectural Decision Making on Data Management in Microservice Architectures” does not report such experimental or model‐based methods; instead, its evaluation centers on qualitative architectural decision making for data management, relying on a decision framework and trade‐off analysis rather than experimental validation.

column103: What are the evaluation methods used by the paper with the title 'Model-Based Analysis of Microservice Resiliency Patterns' compared to the evaluation methods applied in the paper with the title 'Supporting Architectural Decision Making on Data Management in Microservice Architectures'?
column104: The evaluation methods used by the paper with the title 'Model-Based Analysis of Microservice Resiliency Patterns' compared to the evaluation methods applied in the paper with the title 'Supporting Architectural Decision Making on Data Management in Microservice Architectures' are as follows: the paper 'Model-Based Analysis of Microservice Resiliency Patterns' uses Technical Experiment as its evaluation method, whereas the paper 'Supporting Architectural Decision Making on Data Management in Microservice Architectures' applies Grounded Theory as its evaluation method.

column4: Based on the available evidence, the evaluation method in “A Blockchain‐Based Micro Economy Platform for Distributed Infrastructure Initiatives” appears to be grounded in empirical validation through demonstration at the International Conference on Software Architecture (ICSA) with a focus on implementation aspects (e.g., using publication year and venue as indicators of experimental validation). In contrast, “Integrating Statistical Response Time Models in Architectural Performance Models” employs an analytical evaluation method where statistical models are combined with architectural performance models—indicating a more model‐driven, simulation‐oriented approach. Thus, while the first paper emphasizes practical empirical validation in a distributed infrastructure context, the second paper focuses on integrating quantitative statistical measures into performance modeling for software architectures.

column4:
Based on the available evidence, only one research object – “Second Research Object 1” – is reported as being evaluated with the Argumentation evaluation method. Although several papers in the context have publication years of 2019 and 2021, the evidence explicitly linking the Argumentation‐based evaluation to a research object is only found for Second Research Object 1. In short, the distribution (by evaluation method “Argumentation” in the period 2019–2021) includes one research object, even though the contributing papers span both 2019 and 2021.

column4: Based on the provided context, there is no paper that unambiguously fulfills both conditions of investigating architectural assumptions and having a publication year of 2019. Although one paper (“Improving the Consistency and Usefulness of Architecture Descriptions: Guidelines for Architects”) is linked to the research object “Architectural Assumptions”, its publication year is not specified. On the other hand, “Safety Analysis Method for Cooperative Driving Systems” is clearly from 2019 but does not exhibit any link to architectural assumptions.

column103: Which papers published in the publication year 2017 investigate the research object Architecture Design Method and have not used input data?
column104: The papers that investigate the research object Architecture Design Method and do not have input data available in the publication year 2017 are 'An Architecture Framework for Modelling and Simulation of Situational-Aware Cyber-Physical Systems', 'Microservice Ambients: An Architectural Meta-Modelling Approach for Microservice Granularity', and 'Design Criteria to Architect Continuous Experimentation for Self-Driving Vehicles'.

column4:
Based on the provided context, the only link to “Architecture Extraction” is given via “First Research Object 1” (see Path‐based Evidence 9) which is contributed to by two publications – 
 • “Identifying Domain-Based Cyclic Dependencies in Microservice APIs Using Source Code Detectors” (Path‐based Evidence 5) and 
 • “Evaluating the Effectiveness of Multi-level Greedy Modularity Clustering for Software Architecture Recovery” (Path‐based Evidence 8). 

However, none of the available evidence associates a publication year (2018 or 2020) directly with these publications. Although some other papers are indicated with publication years (e.g. Evidence 12 points to a paper in 2018; Evidence 14 and 16 point to papers in 2020), none of those papers are directly connected (through a “research object” relationship) to “Architecture Extraction.” 

Thus, from the provided context the answer is that no paper investigating the research object “Architecture Extraction” can be clearly assigned to 2018 or 2020 – the two papers linked to “Architecture Extraction” do not have a specified publication year in the evidence.
